# DSA Foundation

## What is Big O Notation?

Big O Notation describes how the running time of an algorithm grows as the input size increases.

It does **not** measure the actual execution time in seconds.

---

# O(1) - Constant Time

The running time remains constant regardless of input size.

Example

```java
System.out.println(arr[5]);
```

Only one operation is performed.

---

# O(n) - Linear Time

The running time grows linearly with the input size.

Example

```java
for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

}
```

If `n` doubles,

the number of iterations approximately doubles.

---

# O(n²) - Quadratic Time

The running time grows quadratically.

Example

```java
for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

    for(int j = 0; j < n; j++) {

    }

}
```

If `n` doubles,

the number of operations becomes approximately four times larger.

